ðŸ“Œ SUPER KEY IN DBMS (NOTES + EXAMPLES)
====================================================================

A SUPER KEY is a set of **one or more attributes**
that can **uniquely identify a record (tuple)** in a table.

A Super Key may contain **extra attributes** along with the
attribute(s) required for uniqueness.

====================================================================
WHY DO WE USE SUPER KEY?
--------------------------------------------------------------------
âœ” To uniquely identify rows in a table  
âœ” To avoid duplicate records  
âœ” To help in identifying candidate keys  
âœ” To maintain data integrity  

====================================================================
DEFINITION (EXAM READY)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
A Super Key is a combination of attributes that
**uniquely identifies each record in a relation**.

====================================================================
EXAMPLE TABLE: STUDENT
--------------------------------------------------------------------
| Roll_No | Aadhaar | Name | Email |
--------------------------------------------------------------------

Possible SUPER KEYS:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
âœ” {Roll_No}  
âœ” {Aadhaar}  
âœ” {Email}  
âœ” {Roll_No, Name}  
âœ” {Roll_No, Email}  
âœ” {Aadhaar, Name}  

NOTE:
Even if **one attribute is enough**, adding extra attributes
still makes it a **Super Key**.

====================================================================
SUPER KEY vs CANDIDATE KEY
--------------------------------------------------------------------
âœ” Super Key:
   â†’ May contain extra attributes  
   â†’ Used to identify records  

âœ” Candidate Key:
   â†’ Minimal Super Key  
   â†’ No extra attributes  

Example:
If {Roll_No, Name} is a Super Key  
Then {Roll_No} is a Candidate Key  

====================================================================
SUPER KEY vs PRIMARY KEY
--------------------------------------------------------------------
âœ” Super Key:
   â†’ Many possible  
   â†’ Can have NULL values  

âœ” Primary Key:
   â†’ Only one per table  
   â†’ Cannot be NULL  
   â†’ Chosen from Candidate Keys  

====================================================================
IMPORTANT POINTS
--------------------------------------------------------------------
âœ” Every Primary Key is a Super Key  
âœ” Every Candidate Key is a Super Key  
âœ” But NOT every Super Key is a Candidate Key  
âœ” Super Key is the **base concept of keys**  

====================================================================
SUMMARY
====================================================================
âœ” Super Key uniquely identifies records  
âœ” May contain extra attributes  
âœ” Used to find Candidate & Primary Keys  
âœ” Fundamental concept in DBMS  

